entEntity/ChildEntity example, and a warning about validation condition changes.\n\nLooking at the actual source code, I can see UserBase defines multiple properties with validation annotations like @Required and @Length, and the User class extends UserBase while overriding the setName method with a different @PropertyName value. The knowledge file presents a simplified version of UserBase showing just the setName method, which is an acceptable minimal extraction. The User class implementation shows it calls the parent's setName method and defines validation logic for insert operations.\n\nThe explanation in the source states that validation conditions set on UserBase.setName—specifically the @Required and @Length annotations—are inherited and used during validation, even though the User class only overrides with @PropertyName. This demonstrates that parent class validation annotations persist unless explicitly overridden. When a setter is overridden with only `@PropertyName` and no validation annotations, the parent class's validation rules carry through unchanged.\n\nFor internationalized applications, I need to register display names through message management rather than relying on `@PropertyName` alone. There are two approaches: either use the messageId attribute within `@PropertyName` to reference specific message keys, or leverage the class name combined with property name as the message identifier.\n\nTo use messageId attributes, I'd specify message keys like PROP0001 and PROP0002 in the annotation, then map those to actual display names in the message table. Alternatively, I can skip `@PropertyName` entirely and configure the validation manager to automatically use the pattern \"ClassName.propertyName\" as the message ID, then define those keys in the message table with their corresponding display names. I'm now looking at the decision criteria for choosing between the two approaches. Method 1 with @PropertyName offers easier message ID management but requires maintaining ID-property mappings and makes entity auto-generation more difficult, while Method 2 using class and property names eliminates the need for @PropertyName annotations but doesn't allow for customization during auto-generation.\n\nThe recommendation is to use Method 2 as the default approach since it provides better productivity benefits for entity auto-generation, and only fall back to Method 1 when specific customer requirements make Method 2 unsuitable.\n\nNow I'm verifying the knowledge file against the source material to check for any inaccuracies. Looking at Section 1, the statement about validation annotations being inherited when only @PropertyName is set in a subclass matches what the source describes, and the point about needing to override the setter when changing validation conditions is also correct.\n\nContinuing through the sections—the code examples are accurate extractions, the warning about the Converter annotation is properly captured, and the information about @PropertyName not supporting internationalized messages through the value attribute is verified. The two methods for specifying message IDs are both correctly documented, and the code examples and message tables in the later sections all align with the source material.\n\nNow I'm reviewing the XML configuration details and message tables for the next section, then examining the pros and cons of both approaches along with the recommendation provided.\n\nLooking at the RST source structure, I can see two main h2 sections covering form inheritance with validation conditions and internationalization of property display names, with three h3 subsections nested underneath the second one. The knowledge file maps these to five sequential sections, which aligns well with the document structure.\n\nChecking the content density across sections—s2 has over 200 characters and the others appear similarly substantial, so there's no concern about sections being too sparse.\n\nNow I'm verifying