te that gets discussed later in section 3. Looking at the source more carefully, it explains that converter annotations are inherited separately from validation annotations—so parent class converter settings persist even when you add validation annotations to a child class. The knowledge file appears to be starting to describe converter annotations but seems cut off mid-sentence.\n\nNow I'm checking the ParentEntity and ChildEntity example to see how both the `@Digits` converter annotation from the parent and the `@NumberRange` validation annotation from the child are applied together.\n\nLet me think through what findings I should actually report here—there's a minor issue with the hints not including the `User` class name that appears throughout the examples, and I should verify whether the section structure matches between the source and knowledge file.\n\nLooking back at the source more carefully, the first code example with `UserBase` is fairly comprehensive with all three properties and their annotations fully shown, though the knowledge file does simplify it somewhat, which is fine. I also notice the second `User` class example demonstrates removing `@Required` while keeping `@Length(max=10)`, and the knowledge file does capture this change correctly. There's also that naming inconsistency where `@ValidateFor(\"insert\")` appears on the `validateForUpdate` method in the original, but that's not something the knowledge file needs to address.\n\nNow I should double-check whether the s5 selection criteria is complete by reviewing what the source actually lists for the different methods.\n\nChecking against the source, all the key points are there: Method 1 covers easy ID management and the need for ID-property mapping, Method 2 covers not needing `@PropertyName` and the trade-off with non-standard ID formats, plus the guidance that Method 2 is normally preferred and Method 1 only when customer constraints require it. Everything's accounted for.\n\nThe only real 